Date: Thu 11 Jul 2013
From: John M Pearce <jpearce@usgs.gov> [edited]


[Re: ProMED-mail Avian influenza (78): USA (AK) potential migration hotspot 20130710.1817010]
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Recent studies have shown that [highly pathogenic influenza virus] Asian H5N1 does not cause severe disease in all bird species and some may carry the virus asymptomatically and thus serve as reservoirs for the virus. Thus, the virus could then be carried to novel regions.

Movement of the virus by migratory birds is thought to have led to the novel emergence of H5N1 in Japan in spring of 2008. Also, there are _Anas_ species that use migratory routes between Asia and Alaska. The northern pintail [_Anas acuta_] for example (see numerous papers by the USGS Alaska Science Center [http://alaska.usgs.gov/science/biology/avian_influenza/index.php] on this species' migration patterns between Asia and Alaska and avian influenza genomics).

Lastly, the map provided in the link shows migratory movements away from the northern portion of Alaska near the Arctic Refuge and not the western portion where the Yukon Delta is located and which is also the study site for the paper discussed in this post.

--
John M Pearce
